The key insight to solve this problem is to calculate the probability of each outcome (the chosen number appearing 0, 1, or 2 times) and then multiply each probability by its corresponding return value. Finally, sum up these products to find the expected return.
1. Calculate the probability of the chosen number appearing 0 times:
   $$\begin{align*}
   P(0) = \frac{3}{4} \cdot \frac{3}{4} = \frac{9}{16}
   \end{align*}$$

2. Calculate the probability of the chosen number appearing 1 time:
   $$\begin{align*}
   P(1) = 2 \cdot \frac{1}{4} \cdot \frac{3}{4} = \frac{6}{16}
   \end{align*}$$

3. Calculate the probability of the chosen number appearing 2 times:
   $$\begin{align*}
   P(2) = \frac{1}{4} \cdot \frac{1}{4} = \frac{1}{16}
   \end{align*}$$

4. Multiply each probability by its corresponding return value and sum up the products:
   $$\begin{align*}
   \text{Expected return} &= P(0) \cdot (-1) + P(1) \cdot (1) + P(2) \cdot (2) \\
                          &= \frac{9}{16} \cdot (-1) + \frac{6}{16} \cdot (1) + \frac{1}{16} \cdot (2) \\
                          &= \frac{-9 + 6 + 2}{16} \\
                          &= -\frac{1}{16}
   \end{align*}$$
The expected return to the player, in dollars, for one roll of the dice is $-\frac{1}{16}$.

The key insight in this problem is to use the given congruence equations to find the value of $x$ modulo $20$. Once we have the value of $x$ modulo $20$, we can easily compute $x^2$ modulo $20$ to find the remainder.
1. Subtract the second congruence equation from the first:
   $$\begin{align*}
   4x &\equiv 8 \pmod{20} \\
   -3x &\equiv -16 \pmod{20} \\
   \hline
   x &\equiv -8 \pmod{20}
   \end{align*}$$

2. Square both sides of the congruence equation:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x &\equiv -8 \pmod{20} \\
   x^2 &\equiv (-8)^2 \pmod{20} \\
   x^2 &\equiv 64 \pmod{20}
   \end{align*}$$

3. Simplify the right-hand side:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x^2 &\equiv 64 \pmod{20} \\
   x^2 &\equiv 4 \pmod{20}
   \end{align*}$$
The remainder when $x^2$ is divided by $20$ is $\boxed{4}$.
